    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Massive young stars are responsible for disrupting their birthplace inside molecular clouds.
Massive stars form in compact clusters, having a major influence on the conditions inside molecular clouds through their winds, ionizing radiation and as supernovae.
The influence of young stellar clusters in the center of the Milky Way has provided direct evidence of how this happens.
On other galaxies such studies have been only capable of focusing on the large scale properties due to limitations in resolution and sensitivity.
This proposal makes use of the unprecedented ALMA cycle 2 capabilities to address this question in the nearby starburst system NGC253.
Our observations aim to map the central starburst of NGC253 with a resolution of a few pc to trace the position and kinematics of both compact stellar clusters and dense molecular gas.
These will provide an integral picture of the interplay between the young stellar clusters and their birthplaces inside molecular clouds.</prp:abstract>
